# Rule: Memory Hierarchy

> User-provided instructions OVERRIDE default behavior. ALWAYS adhere to memory file
> contents — they represent explicit user intent.

## Memory File Loading Order

Loading happens in REVERSE order of priority (last loaded = highest priority):

| # | Layer | Path | Scope |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Managed** | `/etc/claude-code/CLAUDE.md` | Enterprise global, all users of the machine |
| 2 | **User** | `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` | Personal global, all of the user's projects |
| 3 | **Project** | `CLAUDE.md`, `.claude/CLAUDE.md`, `.claude/rules/*.md` | Shared via repo, everyone on the team |
| 4 | **Local** | `CLAUDE.local.md` | Private per project, `.gitignore`-able |

**Conflict resolution priority:** Local > Project > User > Managed

## File Discovery Protocol

1. **User memory**: always read from `~/.claude/`
2. **Project + Local**: discovery by directory traversal — from `cwd` up to `/`
3. **Files closer to cwd have higher precedence** (loaded later)
4. In each directory, check:
   - `CLAUDE.md` (canonical)
   - `.claude/CLAUDE.md` (canonical alternative)
   - Every `*.md` in `.claude/rules/` (sub-rules)
5. Always read `CLAUDE.local.md` BEFORE `CLAUDE.md` in the same directory (Local overrides)

## `@include` Directive

Memory files support transitive inclusion of other files:

### Syntax
| Form | Resolves to |
|---|---|
| `@path/to/file.md` | Relative to the current file |
| `@./relative/path.md` | Relative to the current file (explicit) |
| `@~/global/path.md` | Relative to `$HOME` |
| `@/absolute/path.md` | Absolute path |

### Rules
- Works only in **leaf text nodes** (NOT inside code blocks)
- **Circular references** are prevented by tracking processed files
- **Non-existent files** are silently ignored (do not fail)
- **Maximum include depth**: 5 levels
- Only **text file** extensions are allowed (blocks images, PDFs, binaries)

### Example
```markdown
# CLAUDE.md (project root)

@~/.claude/personal-style.md
@./.claude/rules/typescript-strict.md
@/etc/team/shared-conventions.md

## Project-specific rules
- Use Bun (not npm)
- Tests in `__tests__/` folders
```

## Frontmatter `paths` (Conditional Injection)

Memory files can have YAML frontmatter with a `paths` glob — they inject only when the active file matches:

```yaml
---
paths:
  - src/components/**
  - "*.tsx"
  - apps/web/**
---

# React component conventions
- Use functional components
- Default export none, named exports only
- Props interface above component
```

Use cases:
- Conventions specific to parts of the monorepo
- Rules that apply only to specific stacks (e.g., React rules only in `*.tsx`)
- Advanced skills/rules that load only in surgical contexts

## Configuration

| Setting | Default | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `MAX_MEMORY_CHARACTER_COUNT` | 40 000 | Maximum recommendation per file (above → degrades performance) |
| `MAX_INCLUDE_DEPTH` | 5 | Maximum depth of transitive `@include` |
| `claudeMdExcludes` | `[]` | Glob patterns to exclude specific CLAUDE.md files |
| HTML comments | stripped | `<!-- ... -->` is removed before injection |

## Best Practices

### ✅ Do

- **Each layer has a distinct purpose**:
  - Managed: company policies (security, compliance)
  - User: personal preferences (style, tooling)
  - Project: team conventions (stack, patterns)
  - Local: private notes (TODOs, current branch, personal context)
- **Use @include for DRY**: extract shared rules and reference them
- **Frontmatter `paths`** for folder-specific rules
- **Comment your CLAUDE.md** with HTML comments — they are stripped on injection but help you
- **Cap at ~40k chars per file** — split via @include if you exceed it

### ❌ Avoid

- ❌ Overriding base rules without understanding the impact
- ❌ Skipping the `.claude/rules/` directory — you lose modular rules
- ❌ Circular symlinks between includes
- ❌ Memory file > 40k chars (degrades token budget)
- ❌ Relying on `Managed` for critical rules without testing a local override
- ❌ Committing `CLAUDE.local.md` (defeats the purpose — put it in .gitignore)

## Integration with OSForge

OSForge uses this hierarchy for deployment:

```
~/.claude/CLAUDE.md           ← User layer (installed by deploy.sh)
~/.claude/SKILLS.md           ← Skills index (122 triggers)
.claude/rules/*.mdc           ← Project layer (12 always-on rules)
CLAUDE.local.md               ← Local layer (untracked)
```

And it supports `@include` to load `.osforge/status.yaml`:

```markdown
# CLAUDE.md (top of file)
@./.osforge/status.yaml
@~/.claude/SKILLS.md
```

This lets the agent automatically load:
1. Current project state (status.yaml)
2. Available skills (SKILLS.md)
3. Without having to repeat this info in every prompt

## Override Semantics

When two layers conflict:

| Conflict | Resolution |
|---|---|
| Local says X, Project says Y | **Local wins** (X) |
| Project says X, User says Y | **Project wins** (X) |
| User says X, Managed says Y | **User wins** (X) — for personal preferences |
| **Critical security in Managed** | Managed WINS (a Local override cannot disable security) |

**Critical exception:** If Managed has the `enforced: true` flag in its frontmatter, it cannot be overridden by lower layers. Reserved for corporate compliance policies.

```yaml
---
enforced: true
paths: ["**"]
---

# Security policy (corporate)
- NEVER commit secrets to git
- ALWAYS use SSO for cloud auth
- NO eval() in production code
```

## Verification

To validate that the hierarchy is working:

```bash
# List loaded memory files in order
claude memory list

# Validate conflict resolution
claude memory resolve <rule-key>

# Debug: see the final injection in the system prompt
claude memory inject --dry-run
```

